UID:86720-1773167400-1773172800@bangaloreinternationalcentre.org
SUMMARY:To Be a Millennial
DESCRIPTION:What does it mean to be a millennial today — especially in India\, where identity\, aspiration\, and belonging are being rewritten in real time? \nThis session brings together two very different books to explore the millennial experience from the inside out: the narratives we construct about ourselves\, the realities we’re forced to confront\, and the persistent tension between personal ambition and societal expectation. \nIn Good Arguments by Deepika Arwind\, fiction becomes a lens for millennial angst and creativity – tracing what Delphi’s story reveals about self-expression and belonging in a rapidly changing India. In Indian Millennials by AM Gautam\, statistics and anecdotes converge to map the priorities\, contradictions\, and quiet rebellions of a generation that defies easy categorisation. \nTogether\, the books ask: how does a novel capture what a survey cannot? What do numbers reveal that personal stories obscure\, and vice versa? Are millennials uniquely misunderstood\, or simply the first generation to document their own confusion so thoroughly? \nThe goal isn’t to arrive at tidy answers. Millennials aren’t monolithic – they are shaped by the stories they inherit\, the structures they push against\, and the tools they use to make sense of it all: fiction\, analysis\, memoir. If anything\, sitting with the questions feels more honest than resolving them. \nWhich\, perhaps\, is the most millennial thing of all. \nA panel discussion with the authors moderated by Arundhati Sridhar will be followed by a Q&A with the audience. \n
URL:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/event/to-be-a-millennial/
LOCATION:Bangalore International Centre\, 7\, 4th Main Road\, Domlur II Stage\, Bangalore\, Karnataka\, 560071\, India
CATEGORIES:Books,Fiction,Nonfiction
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/wp-content/uploads/Thumbnail-20-3.jpg
END:VEVENT
